<?php

return [
    'Vani Colchis Coin' => 'Silver coinage associated with ancient Colchis circulated across western Georgia and the eastern Black Sea region. Coins found at and around Vani help archaeologists study trade, political authority, and the adoption of monetary exchange alongside older forms of wealth. Their designs connect local symbols with the broader visual language of Mediterranean coinage. Together with imported pottery and luxury metalwork, they show that Colchis participated in long-distance commercial networks while maintaining a distinct regional culture.',
    'Gelati Gospel Manuscript' => 'Gospel manuscripts produced or preserved in Georgian monasteries joined sacred text with calligraphy, decorated initials, miniature painting, and carefully made bindings. Gelati Monastery, founded by David the Builder, became an important center of worship, education, translation, and manuscript culture. A manuscript from this environment represents many specialists: parchment makers, scribes, correctors, painters, and binders. Marginal notes can also preserve the names of donors, historical events, repairs, journeys, and the communities that protected a book through centuries of political change.',
    'Svan Defensive Tower' => 'The stone towers of Svaneti rise beside family houses in compact mountain settlements. Most surviving examples are associated with the medieval period, although many were repaired and reused across generations. Their thick walls and elevated entrances offered refuge during local conflict, while upper openings allowed observation and defense. Towers also expressed family continuity and status. The surrounding villages, farmland, churches, and paths are part of the same cultural landscape, demonstrating how communities adapted architecture to steep terrain, heavy snow, isolation, and the need for collective protection.',
    'King Tamar Period Cross' => 'This representative devotional cross evokes the metalwork and Christian patronage of Georgia during the reign of King Tamar. Crosses could be carried in processions, displayed on altars, placed in reliquaries, or donated by rulers and nobles to important churches. Georgian craftsmen worked with silver, gold, precious stones, repoussé decoration, inscriptions, and enamel. Such objects were not merely ornaments: they expressed theology, dynastic legitimacy, commemoration, and relationships between royal courts, monasteries, and regional workshops during the Georgian Golden Age.',
    'Caucasian Shashka' => 'The shashka is a single-edged sabre that became the characteristic cavalry sidearm of the Caucasus, including Georgia, during the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. It is recognised by a gently curved blade, the absence of a cross-guard, and a hooked hilt that is drawn directly from an open-topped scabbard, allowing a fast cut from horseback. Blades were often obtained through regional and imported trade, while hilts, scabbards, mounts, and shoulder belts were frequently made or decorated locally in silver with niello and engraving. A shashka served at once as a practical weapon, a status object, and an element of formal dress. Wear, repairs, maker’s marks, and the composition of the steel allow specialists to reconstruct an object’s working life and the exchange networks that linked Georgian and neighbouring Caucasian craft traditions.',
    'Ananuri Church Icon' => 'Icons at fortified church complexes such as Ananuri connected private devotion with public worship and noble patronage. Painters used prepared wooden panels, mineral and organic pigments, gold or metal coverings, and inscriptions that identified holy figures. Repeated religious subjects followed established Christian models, yet faces, clothing, colors, and decorative details could reflect Georgian regional practice. An icon’s later history may include repainting, smoke damage, protective coverings, relocation, or restoration, all of which reveal how communities continued to value and use sacred images.',
    'Trialeti Gold Cup' => 'The gold cup associated with the Trialeti archaeological culture belongs to the extraordinary wealth discovered in Middle Bronze Age burial mounds of southern Georgia. Its thin hammered body, precise form, and luxurious material demonstrate advanced metalworking and access to controlled resources. Rich vessels were placed with selected individuals in monumental graves, suggesting ritual feasting, social hierarchy, and the display of elite power. Trialeti objects also show connections across the South Caucasus and Near East while retaining distinctive local forms. Their excavation transformed modern understanding of prehistoric societies in Georgia.',
    'Didgori-period Battle Axe' => 'This representative battle axe illustrates the type of practical military equipment used in the Caucasus around the era of David the Builder. Medieval armies combined royal guards, noble retinues, regional levies, mounted archers, and allied forces, so their weapons varied greatly in form and quality. An axe could deliver a powerful blow while remaining less costly to produce than an elaborate sword. Archaeological examples are studied through blade shape, socket construction, metal composition, and find context. The object helps connect famous victories such as Didgori with the material realities of training, supply, repair, and close combat.',
    'Dmanisi Hominin Skull' => 'The hominin fossils from Dmanisi are among the earliest well-dated remains of Homo found outside Africa, approximately 1.85 to 1.77 million years old. Five remarkably preserved skulls, jaws, teeth, postcranial bones, and simple stone tools were recovered with extinct animal remains beneath the medieval site. The fossils show considerable variation within one population, influencing debates about early human species and migration. Dmanisi suggests that relatively small-brained early humans could adapt to Eurasian environments without later stone-tool technologies. It is one of Georgia’s most important contributions to world prehistory.',
    'Bolnisi Sioni Inscription' => 'The inscriptions at Bolnisi Sioni Cathedral are among the earliest securely dated examples of written Georgian. Carved in Asomtavruli script, they belong to the construction history of the late fifth-century basilica and include a date corresponding to 493/494. Their monumental letters were meant to be seen as part of sacred architecture rather than read from a portable page. The texts provide evidence for early Georgian literacy, Christian patronage, personal names, and the political world of Kartli under Sasanian influence. They are essential for studying both the Georgian alphabet and the emergence of a distinctive church-building tradition.',
    'Khakhuli Triptych' => 'The Khakhuli Triptych is one of the masterpieces of medieval Georgian metalwork. Its surviving arrangement incorporates more than one hundred Georgian and Byzantine cloisonné enamels made between the eighth and twelfth centuries, gathered around a revered image of the Theotokos. Gold, gems, enamel, and repoussé work turned the icon into a brilliant devotional and dynastic object. The triptych was associated with Khakhuli Monastery in Tao and was later moved to Gelati. Its complex history reflects artistic exchange, royal patronage, pilgrimage, loss, reassembly, and modern museum preservation.',
    'The Knight in the Panther’s Skin Manuscript' => 'Shota Rustaveli’s The Knight in the Panther’s Skin was composed around the turn of the thirteenth century and became the defining secular literary work of Georgia’s Golden Age. The poem explores friendship, loyalty, love, courage, and ethical kingship through heroes who move across an imagined international world. Surviving manuscripts are later than the original composition and differ in decoration, handwriting, completeness, and commentary. Families copied and treasured the poem for generations, and illustrated versions became important works of art. Manuscript evidence allows scholars to trace how Rustaveli’s text was read, edited, taught, and transformed.',
    'Jvari Monastery' => 'Jvari Monastery stands on a mountain above Mtskheta at the meeting of the Mtkvari and Aragvi rivers. The present church was built in the late sixth and early seventh centuries around a site associated with Saint Nino’s cross. Its compact tetraconch plan, balanced exterior masses, carved reliefs, and commanding relationship to the landscape made it a model for later churches across Georgia and Armenia. Inscriptions name important patrons and connect architecture with the ruling elite of Kartli. Jvari survives with unusual integrity and forms part of the UNESCO-listed historical monuments of Mtskheta.',
    'Vani Bronze Figurine' => 'Bronze sculpture recovered at Vani belongs to an exceptional archaeological landscape of sanctuaries, elite buildings, burials, workshops, and imported objects. Cast figures and attachments reveal advanced metalworking, careful observation of the human body, and participation in artistic networks around the Black Sea. Their archaeological context connects visual culture with ritual practice and the changing political fortunes of ancient Colchis.',
    'Armazi Bilingual Stele' => 'The Armazi bilingual inscription was discovered in the elite cemetery at Armaziskhevi near ancient Mtskheta. Its Greek and Armazic texts commemorate Serapitis, a young woman connected with the royal court of Iberia. The stele provides unusually direct evidence for personal identity, court titles, literacy, multilingual administration, funerary commemoration, and the international connections of eastern Georgia in the Roman era.',
    'Kura-Araxes Ceramic Vessel' => 'Kura-Araxes pottery is recognized by carefully shaped forms, burnished surfaces, and contrasting black and red colors created through controlled firing. Such vessels occur at settlements and graves across Georgia and a much wider region. Their distribution helps archaeologists investigate household practice, food preparation, mobility, technological knowledge, and cultural interaction during the Early Bronze Age.',
    'Narikala Fortress' => 'Narikala occupies a steep ridge above the old districts of Tbilisi and the Mtkvari River. The fortress changed repeatedly as rulers strengthened the city, repaired damage, and adapted defenses to new military technologies. Its walls preserve the strategic importance of Tbilisi at a crossing point between regions, while the surviving landscape connects fortification, royal authority, trade routes, bath districts, and urban memory.',
    'Uplistsikhe Cave City' => 'Uplistsikhe was carved into sandstone above the Mtkvari River and developed as a major political, religious, and commercial center. Rock-cut halls, streets, drainage channels, wine installations, dwellings, defensive works, and ritual spaces document long occupation. A medieval church built among earlier structures makes the site especially valuable for studying religious and urban transformation rather than a single frozen moment.',
    'Dmanisi Medieval Citadel' => 'Long after early humans occupied the area, medieval Dmanisi became a fortified city controlling routes between Georgia, Armenia, and the wider Near East. Excavated walls, gates, churches, houses, workshops, coins, ceramics, and imported goods reveal a diverse commercial center. Its decline followed invasions and shifting trade, leaving an unusually rich archaeological record beneath and around the citadel.',
    'Svetitskhoveli Cathedral' => 'Svetitskhoveli Cathedral was constructed in the early eleventh century under Catholicos Melchizedek and architect Arsukidze, on a site associated with Georgia’s earliest Christian traditions. Its cross-domed interior, carved façades, chapels, tombs, frescoes, and inscriptions unite worship with royal commemoration. Repeated repairs and restorations demonstrate the cathedral’s continuing national and ecclesiastical importance.',
    'Gelati Monastery' => 'David IV founded Gelati in 1106 as a royal monastery and intellectual center near Kutaisi. Its main church preserves a celebrated apse mosaic and extensive layers of fresco painting, while the wider complex includes churches, gates, an academy, and the king’s burial place. Gelati embodies the political confidence, theological learning, artistic exchange, and educational ambition of Georgia’s Golden Age.',
    'Alaverdi Cathedral' => 'Alaverdi Cathedral rises dramatically from the Alazani Valley on a monastic site associated with the sixth-century missionary Joseph of Alaverdi. The present cathedral was built under King Kvirike III of Kakheti in the early eleventh century. Its great height, disciplined masonry, interior painting, defensive enclosure, wine culture, and long episcopal history make it a central monument of eastern Georgia.',
